Hello all. I seem to have stumbled upon a rather weird possible regression after I migrated from SDK 3.1.102 to 3.1.200.

**Context**
A few days ago I forked the VSCode extension [formulahendry/vscode-dotnet-test-explorer](https://github.com/formulahendry/vscode-dotnet-test-explorer) and started playing around with bringing it up to speed for Core SDK 3.1 and doing some other changes. For testing my changes, I was using the solution I work on at my job.

The extension first discovers possible test projects in a VSCode workspace and then executes `dotnet test -t -v=q [project]` against one project at a time. It waits until the execution terminates and reads the stdout in order to retrieve the list of tests. This list is further processed and displayed etc.

While I was using the SDK 3.1.102, everything was working perfectly here. The command produced the list of tests every time without issues. However, after I updated to SDK 3.1.200, this started failing in more than 50% of executions (but not always).

**The issue**
In SDK 3.1.200, the `dotnet test -t -v=q [project path]` terminates but it looks like the stdout is not properly flushed. The extension reads the stdout and only  gets as far as
```
Test run for [pathToDll](.NETCoreApp,Version=v3.1)
Microsoft (R) Test Execution Command Line Tool Version 16.5.0
Copyright (c) Microsoft Corporation.  All rights reserved.

The following Tests are available:
```
And that's it. No tests are listed in the stdout (even though they are there, of course). If I run the same command from the command line, the output is complete (with tests), but there is an observable pause between outputting `The following Tests are available:` and the actual list of tests.

To verify the regression theory, I introduced a global.json and used it to fix a specific SDK version for the solution in question. The results are consistent - 3.1.102 works every time, 3.1.200 fails more often then not.

Since the problem does not manifest every time, it feels like a possible race condition to me. If the `dotnet` process terminates too quickly, the stdout isn't flushed completely and whatever is in the buffer gets lost. But it's really just a theory.

**The problematic code**
``` ts
function executeDotnetTest(testDirectoryPath: string, dotnetTestOptions: string): Promise<string> {
    return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
        Logger.Log(`Executing dotnet test -t -v=q in ${testDirectoryPath}`);

        let buffer = "";

        const p = cp.spawn("dotnet", ["test", "-t", "-v=q" ], { cwd: testDirectoryPath });
        p.stdout.on("data", (data) => buffer += data.toString());
        p.on("close", (code) => {
            if (code !== 0) {
                Logger.LogError(`Error while executing dotnet test -t -v=q`, code);

                reject();
            }

            Logger.Log(buffer);

            resolve(buffer);
        });
    });
}
```
Now I'm not the greatest with Node.js but this should work and does work when using the older SDK. It spawns a new process with the necessary parameters, hooks to the stdout to build a buffer, then, when the process closes all its IO streams, logs the buffer and resolves the promise.

More details: the projects in question use xUnit for testing framework, but it also reproduces with MSTest.

**Question**
Can someone please try and clarify what's going on here? Or possibly offer a workaround?
